---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import LessonShell from "../../components/LessonShell.astro";
import DesignSim from "../../components/DesignSim.astro";
import { LESSONS } from "../../data/curriculum";

const lesson = LESSONS.find((l) => l.id === "design-first")!;
---

<Layout title={`${lesson.title} · Learn AI`} currentId="design-first">
  <main>
    <LessonShell lesson={lesson}>
      <p>
        <strong>UI generators</strong> turn a sentence into a working piece of interface — real HTML/React,
        not a mockup. Type a prompt, see it render, tweak, iterate, copy the code.
      </p>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Product</th><th>Output</th><th>From</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>v0.dev</td><td>React / Next.js components</td><td>Vercel</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Lovable</td><td>Full-stack apps (React + DB)</td><td>Lovable</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Bolt.new</td><td>Full-stack apps, in-browser dev</td><td>StackBlitz</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Claude Design</td><td>HTML / React components</td><td>Anthropic</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Galileo</td><td>UI mockups + design systems</td><td>Galileo AI</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <p>The imitation below shows the shared pattern: prompt → canvas preview → variants. Try the chips and the Warm / Dark / Brutalist buttons.</p>

      <DesignSim />

      <h2>The prompt template that works</h2>
      <pre>A [type of screen] for [audience].
[Two or three style words]. Include [content].</pre>

      <h2>Style words that pull the result</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Tone:</strong> playful · serious · premium · retro · brutalist · soft · technical · friendly</li>
        <li><strong>Density:</strong> generous whitespace · compact · dashboard-dense</li>
        <li><strong>Reference:</strong> "like Linear" · "like a Japanese menu" · "like an old paperback"</li>
      </ul>
    </LessonShell>
  </main>
</Layout>
